  "prompt": "What is the candela? What is it used for?",
  "response": "The candela (cd) is the base unit of luminous intensity in the International System of Units (SI). Here are key details about the candela:\n\nDefinition:\n- One candela is the luminous intensity, in a given direction, of a source that emits monochromatic radiation of frequency 540 \u00d7 10\u00b9\u00b2 hertz and has a radiant intensity in that direction of 1/683 watt per steradian.\n\nUses:\n1. Measuring light brightness and intensity\n2. Defining light output for various sources like:\n- Light bulbs\n- LEDs\n- Flashlights\n- Streetlights\n- Projectors\n\nPractical applications:\n- Designing lighting systems\n- Determining visibility and illumination levels\n- Specifying lighting requirements for different environments\n- Helping create standards for light sources\n- Enabling precise comparisons of light output across different devices\n\nThe candela allows for standardized measurement of luminous intensity, which is crucial in fields like architecture, photography, automotive design, and lighting engineering.\n\nIt's one of the seven base units in the SI system and plays a critical role in quantifying and comparing light sources objectively.",
